review: Oh, this was delightful! It is essentially one of my absolute favorite literary tropes- a grumpy, lonely older protagonist who has a coming-of-age jouOh, this was delightful! It is essentially one of my absolute favorite literary tropes- a grumpy, lonely older protagonist who has a coming-of-age journey through the help of their lovely, diverse, wacky community. I can probably name 5 books that I love that all follow this pattern, and I'm happy to add Albert Entwhistle to the list. It was a lovely, heartwarming journey and I adored all of his coworkers and neighbors. The only drawback (and this is truly petty and ridiculous) is that it is just SO heavily British (ya know, as it's a British book taking place in Britain written by a British author) that my stunted American English brain had to work (and Google) overtime to work out the British colloquialisms, slang, terms, and so on. This is absolutely an "it's not you, it's me" problem, so I'm not holding it against the book at all- it just explains why I stayed a tiny bit emotionally removed and read it a bit slower than I otherwise would've. But overall- absolutely loved it!...more

I learned a ton, though truly the bottom line of the whole book is that almost everything about the human body is still a mystery. This is a book I can see myself wanting to go back and refer to in the future, as I will surely recall vague details about something or the other and wish to remember the whole story. I was torn between 4 and 5 stars…it WAS a suuuuper long book, which I often deduct points for, but truly- it was worth it. There was very little superfluous or unnecessary, so I don’t know where he would’ve cut length. review: Oh man, this is a tough one to rate- honestly, the first ~60% was kind of a struggle for me. It was interesting, but VERY detailed and lots of long plOh man, this is a tough one to rate- honestly, the first ~60% was kind of a struggle for me. It was interesting, but VERY detailed and lots of long play-by-plays of different battles and skirmishes and 'sorties', and it was just...a slog. The interspersed chapters of the Soviet delegation in Washington were more interesting, but many of the chapters of life on the front were tedious. However, once I got to around 60% the story really picked up and I was finally sucked in. The final 40% was fantastic, compelling, and fast-moving. I'm utterly obsessed with Mila's friendship with Eleanor Roosevelt and have already embarked on some fascinating internet deep dives into that. Since I obviously had to pause the book around 75% and frantically read Mila's entire Wikipedia entry so that I could know what was going to happen, I really found the Author's Note at the end to add a lot- I loved hearing Quinn say where she created characters and events, and what was verbatim from Mila's own accounts. Overall, the first 60% was a tough 2.5 stars, but the last part was like 8 stars, so we'll make the math land at a strong 4 stars overall. Definitely recommend!...more

review: Whew. This was tough. In many ways this reminded me of “A Place for Us,” which is no small thing coming from me- that’s probably my favorite book of tWhew. This was tough. In many ways this reminded me of “A Place for Us,” which is no small thing coming from me- that’s probably my favorite book of the last 5 years. In “The Leavers” we follow similarly complicated protagonists, experiencing a story from one perspective and then another, the second telling usually reframing what you believed from the first. We have complex immigrant stories and family relationships. Both of the main characters are layered and flawed. It was really good, and deeply thought-provoking. It doesn’t glamorize adoption or foster care, but centers the experience of the adoptee and the mother whose child was wrongfully taken from her, and it isn’t easy to read. This wasn’t really a fun book, but it was so good and deeply important. I definitely recommend. ...more

review: Hm. This is tough. I’ll start with the positives. I loved the writing. I liked the alternating narrators. The plot was promising. But. I ultimately diHm. This is tough. I’ll start with the positives. I loved the writing. I liked the alternating narrators. The plot was promising. But. I ultimately didn’t feel great about a white British dude writing from the perspective of a young female Nigerian refugee and her reluctant white British female “savior” (Little Bee’s cringy words, not mine). I’m not of the mindset that authors should only write characters of their own perspective and experience 100% of the time. There’s room for some nuance there, I think. But in this situation, I just didn’t care for it. I also really didn’t enjoy how blatantly he positioned Sarah as the White Savior. It was icky. Additionally, there were a lot of heavy topics covered: genocide, gang rape, suicide, immigration/refugees…and though I felt like those were generally dealt with delicately and not graphically, it was just a lot to deal with on top of everything else. And I just didn’t feel like the “resolution” was as good as maybe the author thought I should. Anyway. When I started writing this  I’d given the book 3 stars, but after writing it and reflecting further, I’m going with 2. I have rarely felt so incredibly anxious and sad due to a story. I have no personal experience with PPD myself, but I now have a deep and intimate knowledge of what it is like for some women, and...damn. This was truly a very difficult book to read, but at the same time I think it was well done and important. I will be thinking about it for a long time, and it certainly opened my eyes to situations I hadn’t considered before. There is some hope in the story, and the last quarter wasn’t as difficult as the first 3/4, if that helps to know. The first 7,000 pages (25% of the book) were just inexcusably, unforgivably, torturously overwrought chapters of world building upon world building. NO. NO THANK YOU. What is happening here with all this world building, SJM? You trying to rival God and the creation story and write a book longer and more comprehensive than the Bible??! Is this like some kind of weird competition between you two? Because no one needs that much world building. Just let us live in the mystery. The next 24,000 pages of the book were interesting but- all together now- TOO LONG. Too many characters and stories and details and Randomly capitalized and Misspell’d wyrds. But I kept going because dammit, it was getting good, and I ultimately I trust SJM and her freaking world building and I knew the pain would be worth it. And the last 10,000 pages really were quite excellent. I mean, sure, it was like a month since I started reading and I’ve mostly forgotten how the world worked anyway, but it’s fine. I was invested. But also- I’m mad, because if there’s a reason I keep returning to SJM, it’s because she writes a spicy romance better than anyone. So someone please tell me why I just spent a month reading six billion pages of world building and NO SPICY ROMANCE FOR MY TROUBLES?! Are we breaking up, SJM? (Just kidding just kidding- we are never breaking up because you hold ACOTAR in your head and heart and I’ll love you forever for it.) review: This was so good. I enjoyed Homegoing, so I was excited for this book, and it definitely surpassed Homegoing for me. Transcendent Kingdom read very muThis was so good. I enjoyed Homegoing, so I was excited for this book, and it definitely surpassed Homegoing for me. Transcendent Kingdom read very much like a memoir to me- in fact, I had to keep stopping to remind myself that it was actually fiction. Gifty's experience growing up in the evangelical faith of her mother was so beautifully written, so poignant and raw and it rang very true to what I experienced myself. Her reflections on her relationships with her brother and mother, mixed with her narration of her ongoing neuroscience research, were exceptionally well done. This book reminds me in many ways of A Place for Us (Fatima Farheen Mirza), which is no small praise from me. Both tell stories of immigrant families adapting to America, integrating and/or struggling with their faith, and touched by mental health and substance abuse issues. A Place for Us made me cry more, but both stories glisten with a quiet hope that will linger long after the book ends. Five stars, for sure....more

review: Man. This is tough. I would have liked this book a lot more if I hadn’t read it directly after finishing A Court of Thorns and Roses series. The back-Man. This is tough. I would have liked this book a lot more if I hadn’t read it directly after finishing A Court of Thorns and Roses series. The back-to-back tales of unassuming young women being thrust into new, magic-filled worlds, chasing romance and wars and justice were just too similar to not constantly be comparing them in my head...and unfortunately, Red Queen just fell far short. The whole story felt rushed, in a timeline sense. Everything just happened too quickly- not in a sense that the story was just really fast paced...more like things that should take at least months to build up in a person or story (resentment, love, commitment to a cause, hatred for a rival) all happened in about 3 days (or 6 pages) and it was just...unsatisfying. review: My daughter and I are loving the Mia Mayhem series! The series begins with this book, where Mia discovers that she is actually a superhero (as are herMy daughter and I are loving the Mia Mayhem series! The series begins with this book, where Mia discovers that she is actually a superhero (as are her parents, unbeknownst to her) and gets to start attending superhero training school. If you're getting serious Harry Potter vibes...so was I. But so fun! The writing style is really fun and upbeat and perfect for reading aloud. My daughter (just turned 6) is a very early reader and would struggle to try to read this on her own, but is super excited to read a "real chapter book" with me, and there are certainly random sentences I'll let her attempt, if they are mostly made up of sight words and easy-to-sound-out words! There are pencil illustrations on all of the pages, which make the stories even easier and more fun to follow along with. My favorite part is how diverse the characters are, in a variety of ways. The title character and her family are Black, Mia's friends and classmates are a variety of races, and you also see superhero kids with differing abilities (wheelchairs, prosthetic limbs). Honestly, the chapter books for kids this age have mostly been so corny and cringeworthy that I dread reading them...so I'm really thankful that Mia is to the rescue here!!! :) ...more

title: Parable of the Sower        (Earthseed, #1)
author: Butler, Octavia E.
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: This book was fascinating in so many ways. It was horrifying in how close to home it hit- it was written in 1993 and takes place in 2024-2027, in a quThis book was fascinating in so many ways. It was horrifying in how close to home it hit- it was written in 1993 and takes place in 2024-2027, in a quickly-crumbling California. The slow collapse of civilization Butler imagined here was completely believable- from where I sit now in 2020, I could easily imagine this as a plausible climate-crisis-driven possibility for our not-so-distant future. It was very uncomfortable to read for that reason. There weren’t zombies or time travel or fairies or anything to distract from how very real and possible the story was. (It reminded me of Station Eleven in that way.) I enjoyed (??? Well that’s not the word for it...appreciated, maybe?) Lauren’s story and journey north. The experience of gathering her group of travelers together and making their way north was compelling and my favorite part of the book. My least favorite part was the actual discussion about Earthseed. It was just a little farfetched and cheesy to me, to imagine a teenage girl in this world creating a religion and expecting others to join her in it. I liked the actual Earthseed poetry at the beginning of the chapters though, so there’s that. My largest complaint about the book, weirdly, was the editing- or lack thereof. There were SO MANY punctuation errors- I’m not sure if it was just the edition I read or what, but random (and missing) quotation marks were evvvverywhere and suuuuper distracting. There were spelling errors, random capITalization erroRs, and just overall the whole thing needed a proofreader to give it a once over. I’m not sure how that is possible in a book so popular and published so many times!! My final complaint is that there were a lot of (not graphic, not explicit) references to children being raped. It was perhaps the casualness that they were spoken of with that was so jarring: “we passed Sue’s eight year old sister’s body, and noticed that she’d been raped. Then we heard a dog and ran to hide from it.” ....for example. But it was rough. Overall it was a compelling book, if not enjoyable. But I am curious enough to want to read the next one and hope for some happiness for the characters I’ve come to appreciate. ...more

title: The Most Fun We Ever Had
author: Lombardo, Claire*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: I really, really liked this. I loooove a good multigenerational family saga and this totally delivered. I was invested in all of the characters and foI really, really liked this. I loooove a good multigenerational family saga and this totally delivered. I was invested in all of the characters and found them all to be relatably imperfect, flawed but lovable. Their personal and interpersonal conflicts were earned and well-explored. I thought the format (narrators and time period frequently changed and with no indications about who was narrating except the context) worked, though you have to spend the first few sentences of every new section figuring out who is talking and what year it is. I'm fine with that. I can see it annoying some people, though. :) As a whole, the book reminded me a lot of A Place for Us by Fatima Mirza, which is easily my favorite book of the last two years and it is no small compliment for me to compare anything to it. There are many similarities in format and content- both explore family relationships over several decades. I loved Lombardo's writing and felt that it perfectly fit the characters and stories in this book. It's not quite as lyrical or contemplative as A Place for Us, which some might think is a good thing, but it didn't need to be, as it also didn't explore the themes of faith and religion that were so expertly done in Mirza's book. I have altogether almost zero complaints about The Most Fun- my extremely minor quibble would be with the inaccuracy of the foster care system portrayed, from my vantage point as a foster and adoptive parent, but it was not glaring and not unbelievable enough to matter to the story. :) And not that this matters either, but I LOVED that I understood both the cover art AND title relatively early in my reading. LOVE THAT. I'm sometimes so annoyed when I'm 80% through a book and still have no idea why it's titled what it is, or what the cover art/picture is all about. So extra points and props to the author/her team for making sure I won't forget the title of this or what it looks like when I'm trying to tell someone about it in a month! In all, this book is a strong 10/10 for me- well worth the (long!) read!...more

review: This book took me FOR-EV-ER to finish. I am really torn about what to rate it. The beginning was fantastic. The middle-ish third was soooo lonnnngggg This book took me FOR-EV-ER to finish. I am really torn about what to rate it. The beginning was fantastic. The middle-ish third was soooo lonnnngggg and really frustrating. I liked the premise of the book. I did NOT care for the addition of magic or magical realism or whatever that was. The journeys to New Orleans were torturously long for me. I wanted to stop reading mannnny times, but I was genuinely curious how the author planned to pull together this many random storylines, characters, and elements. The very end (like 50 pages....out of 400+) picked up a little, but I wouldn’t say it was actually satisfying. I dunno. The beginning felt so strong, with the loss of shadows and the forgetting. I wish the story had stuck with that and the ensuing world building (or falling apart, as the case may be) and not taken the hard turn into fantasy and magic (and I’m generally a fan of magic, but here we are). My heart says two stars because I really had to work to finish it, but man the beginning was good, so I’ll go with three for now. 🤷🏻‍♀️...more

This was the book I needed right now, and now I’m going to buy it so that I can savor it better without library due dates lurking over my shoulder. review: 3.5 stars, but rounding up because I feel like most of the struggles I had with this book were my own fault. Basically this book reminded me that I kn3.5 stars, but rounding up because I feel like most of the struggles I had with this book were my own fault. Basically this book reminded me that I know nothing about WWI. Not a thing. And therefore I struggled mightily with following the war-heavy storylines of this book- the descriptions of the front moving from here to there, and the such and such army doing this, and honestly I barely even understood/recalled the alliances between countries, much less the relationships between different ethnic groups within certain cities of ??Austria?? and ??Poland??— question marks indicating I generally didn’t even know where we were in the story. It was tough. I had to Google A LOT. BUT technical issues aside, I liked the story. The characters and situations were compelling. The writing was well done, and I loved the (sometimes grotesque) insight into medicine on the war front. Much of the book was fascinating. But then i would get so lost in the war part that it kind of put a damper on the whole experience for me. So I’m torn. I think that if someone were a WWI buff with a keen interest and knowledge of the intricacies of what was going on...I would recommend this book. But for a more casual student of history who is just looking for a compelling story- maybe pass on this one. ***After sleeping on it, I am changing my rating to three stars. Turns out that every time I see the book sitting on the table, I have a feeling of relief wash over me that I’m done with it and don’t have to read it anymore. review: I don't even know where to start with this book. It is beautiful, deep, moving, and heart-wrenching. An incredibly well-written book focused on characI don't even know where to start with this book. It is beautiful, deep, moving, and heart-wrenching. An incredibly well-written book focused on characters, relationships, and questions of faith. Some of the writing felt like poetry in the best possible way. I'm not sure what genre I would put this book in, but I would wholeheartedly recommend it to anyone looking for a deep, nuanced look at family relationships. I loved the style of the book- alternating narrators sharing stories across decades of time. In another author's hands, it may have felt chaotic or disconnected, but Mirza truly wove the story together beautifully. The story about the family taking a picnic beside the river has really resonated with me in my own parenting journey and is something I will probably think about for a long time. The entire fourth section was just a masterpiece- although I struggled to read through my tears. All in all...this book was just everything I didn't know I needed. As a non-Muslim, I deeply appreciate how thoughtfully and beautifully Mirza wove the characters' faith (and struggles with faith) through the story. The faith questions the characters individually struggled with felt so familiar to me, despite our religious differences. And at the end of the book, Rafiq's realizations and revelations about mercy simply had me weeping. Five shining, glittery stars. I cannot wait to see what else Fatima Mirza brings us....more

review: I liked a lot of things about this book. I loved the behind-the-scenes look at the campaigns and life in the White House. I feel like I learned a lot I liked a lot of things about this book. I loved the behind-the-scenes look at the campaigns and life in the White House. I feel like I learned a lot about how things actually get done in the WH- I especially liked the parts about dealing with natural disasters. Very insightful. Alyssa was self-deprecating and approachable, and I liked learning about her non-Ivy-League path to the WH. However, the non-chronological style of the book was really off-putting to me. I had a lot of trouble keeping up with who was who (all the nicknames didn't help that), who was doing what job, and where we were in time. I know that the chapters were supposed to be organized by theme or idea, but I think I would have just preferred a more chronological memoir with all of the anecdotes and tidbits (that I did love). I thought the random chapters of lists and advice were rather out of place and strange. Overall, it wasn't a great book for me, but I did enjoy it and am still glad for the insight I got into the WH and the more personal look at President Obama. It was a fast read, if a bit disorganized, and I did glean some useful tips and information. ...more

title: My Absolute Darling
author: Tallent, Gabriel*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: **spoiler alert** I have really struggled with how to rate this book. Overall, I found the story to be depressing, disturbing, and rather pretentious.**spoiler alert** I have really struggled with how to rate this book. Overall, I found the story to be depressing, disturbing, and rather pretentious. But there were moments of beauty- or potential for beauty- and although there were altogether WAY TOO MANY ADJECTIVES and descriptions, I still found it to be a swift, compelling read. I think that like many readers, my chief issue is with the way Turtle’s repeated sexual assaults by her father are portrayed. The languages used was far too sympathetic. I understand that Turtle was confused, conflicted, and had some Stockholm syndrome going on, but I felt that the repeated insensitivity of language and gratuitous and graphic violence very much detracted from the overall book. After the first few chapters- okay, we get it. Martin is a sadistic pedophile. If you need to allude to the continuing assaults, fine, but we can stop reading about her “engorged pussy” already. Same with the gun stuff. We get it. There are a ton of guns, Turtle is a genius at shooting, she cleans them all the time, Martin has weird obsessions with shooting practice, whatever. Enough ten-page play-by-plays of that. I found Turtle’s fascination/relationship with Jake and Brett to be the more compelling part of the story, as well as her eventually trying to figure a way out (and then with Cayenne as well) and wish we could have had more of that and less guns and rape. And I very much wish we could have had more story devoted to “after”...seeing Turtle learn to integrate into normal society would have been a more compelling story than another encounter with her father. Overall, I’m torn because I do think there were some interesting aspects of the story that I’d love to discuss with my book club, but I would never actually recommend that any of them read the book because it just wasn’t worth the disturbing parts. 2.5 stars, but I round down for how irritated I was by the romanticized portrayal of rape. ...more

This book was an enjoyable read, probably because I just really like survival stories, but not the most solid story. I just didn’t think the “big secrets” were really big enough to merit all the lies and build-up. So all of the “present” chapters felt a little unnecessarily dramatic...why wouldn’t they have just told the truth about Paul? I understand (and liked) the story and lie about Kent, but I feel like everything else was understandable and not worth lying about. Overall an easy read, but too much unnecessary drama. Also, egg donation is not something that can be accomplished in one quick secret trip to the fertility clinic. 😂😂😂 as a fertility clinic veteran, that gave me the major eye rolls. ...more

review: Ehhhh. Not my favorite Charles Martin book. This story felt way too heavy on the religion and too light on story development. I felt that Miss Ella waEhhhh. Not my favorite Charles Martin book. This story felt way too heavy on the religion and too light on story development. I felt that Miss Ella was waaay too stereotypical and one-dimensional. I liked the other main characters (Tuck, Mutt, Katie), but I didn’t really understand one of the huge points the story was built on- why was Rex raising the boys in the first place? What happened to their moms? Why did Tuck and Mutt have no issues with being abandoned/unwanted by their mothers? Did they die? I just can’t imagine a scenario that would leave them in sole custody of Rex except death, and both of them dying seems like a stretch. I will keep reading Charles Martin stories because I loved The Mountain Between Us and Unwritten so much, but this book was simply not in the same category as those. ...more
